Also it had pastore land which was never inclosed or enjoyed in severalty, ‘the green commons ol the town’; ior the more part they are green and open still. But further, so late as the reign ol James I, Cambridge, its fields and its green commons can upon occasion be treated as an agrarian whole. In 1624 the Vice·Chancellor os the University and the Mayor ol the Borough issued an ordinance touching the commons of the town. Every occupier oi an ancient tenement having o's old time broad gates may turn out two head ol cattle. Every occupier os other tenements and cottages may turn out one. Every person having six score acres of land in Cambridge field may turn out six, and so in proportion for any greater or less quantity os land¹.

“ Observe what this reverend Vice-Chancellor and this worshiplul Mayor are doing. They seem to be legislating for an agrarian commonwealth. They are decreeing that the pasture of the town must still subserve the arable of the town. And what is the unitos arable that gives the normal share ol pastore-right? Itis six score acres, a long hundred of acres, a hide².”

The peculiar configuration oi the town os Cambridge- an ellipse with its major diameter north and south, and the river Cam flowing along its western side-divides the adjacent fields into two groups, eastern and western. I shall take the sormer group first, but, belore the relations oi these fields to one another are discussed, I must ask my readers to dismiss all ideas derived from the Cambridge os today. My object is to reproduce the fields as they were when the town was in the condition 1 have been trying to describe, and when, as Professor Maitland has said, “il a burgess of Cambridge crossed the ditch, he came out at

once, or almost at once, upon the great sheet of ploughed land⁸.'’
